    {
      "id": "concept-caching",
      "title": "Caching",
      "description": "Caching stores frequently accessed data in fast memory (e.g. Redis, Memcached) to reduce load on the database and improve response time.  Using a cache layer can dramatically speed up read-heavy workloads (e.g. serving hot user sessions or product data) and lower latency.  For example, web applications often cache database query results or session objects in distributed in-memory stores to avoid repeated expensive lookups. Enhanced with additional resources and perspectives.",
      "estimatedMinutes": 60,
      "difficulty": "Beginner",
      "category": "Core Fundamentals",
      "orderIndex": 2,
