    {
      "id": "concept-databases-sql-vs-nosql",
      "title": "Databases (SQL vs NoSQL)",
      "description": "Database selection and design are core to system design. Relational (SQL) databases use fixed schemas and ACID transactions, suitable for structured data and strict consistency; they generally scale vertically (bigger machines). NoSQL databases (key-value, document, columnar) are schema-flexible and horizontally scalable, often providing high availability and eventual consistency (BASE) to handle massive data. The choice affects sharding, indexing, and consistency models. Enhanced with additional resources and perspectives.",
      "estimatedMinutes": 120,
      "difficulty": "Beginner",
      "category": "Core Fundamentals",
      "orderIndex": 4,
