    {
      "id": "concept-indexing",
      "title": "Indexing",
      "description": "Indexes in databases provide fast lookup of records by maintaining a separate data structure (like a B-tree) that maps keys to row locations.  Without an index, queries must scan entire tables; with an index, the DB can quickly find rows matching a key. For example, indexing on a 'user_id' column allows O(log n) searches rather than full table scans. However, indexes increase write costs, so they must be judiciously chosen.",
      "estimatedMinutes": 60,
      "difficulty": "Intermediate",
      "category": "Core Fundamentals",
      "orderIndex": 8,
