    {
      "id": "concept-idempotency",
      "title": "Idempotency",
      "description": "Idempotency means that repeating an operation (e.g. retrying a request) has the same effect as doing it once.  This is crucial for retries in distributed systems.  For example, using unique request IDs or client tokens, a POST can be made idempotent: if a retry with the same token arrives, the server realizes it already applied the change.  Idempotent design prevents duplicate actions on retries.",
      "estimatedMinutes": 45,
      "difficulty": "Advanced",
      "category": "Core Fundamentals",
      "orderIndex": 17,
      "resources": [
