    {
      "id": "concept-transactions-acid-vs-base",
      "title": "Transactions (ACID vs BASE)",
      "description": "Transactions group multiple operations into an atomic action.  Traditional RDBMS enforce ACID properties (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) for reliability.  However, distributed systems often adopt a BASE model (Basically Available, Soft-state, Eventual consistency) to achieve partition tolerance.  For example, a bank transfer in an RDBMS is ACID; a large-scale shopping cart checkout may allow eventual consistency between inventory systems for better availability.",
      "estimatedMinutes": 60,
      "difficulty": "Advanced",
      "category": "Core Fundamentals",
      "orderIndex": 18,
      "resources": [
